US Bank Earnings Update

Key Earnings Insights

Growth And Profitability - Citigroup

Citigroup demonstrates strong growth and profitability, with net income up nearly 40% for the full year and revenues exceeding targets, growing 5% ex divestitures. Key drivers include fee revenue growth, positive operating leverage in core businesses, and a strong performance in Markets, Services, and Banking. The company is adjusting its 2026 RoTCE target to between 10% and 11% to account for required investments in transformation and technology.

  • "For the full year, our net income was up nearly 40% to $12.7 billion. We exceeded our full year revenue target with revenues up 5% ex divestitures."
  • "Our 5 core businesses each generated positive operating leverage for the full year, which we also achieved at the firm level."

Lending Activities - Citigroup

Lending activities show positive trends, particularly in USPB (U.S. Personal Banking), driven by borrowing across card portfolios, leading to revenue increases. Citigroup is strategically strengthening its lending business through partnerships and acquisitions, such as the extended co-branded partnership with American Airlines and the acquisition of the Barclays portfolio. Furthermore, Citi is bringing in new talent to lead lending activities.

  • "USPB revenues were up 6%, driven by borrowing across both card portfolios and by fee growth."
  • "We announced a 10-year extension of our co-branded partnership with American Airlines ensuring that this valuable relationship enters into its fifth decade."

Credit Performance - Citigroup

Citigroup maintains a robust credit profile with over $22 billion in total reserves. Cost of credit was $2.6 billion, largely consisting of cards, net credit losses and ACL build. The reserve-to-funded loan ratio stands at 2.7%. While there are limited details, these levels show strong reserve coverage.

  • "Cost of credit was $2.6 billion, largely consisting of cards, net credit losses and ACL build."
  • "At the end of the quarter, we had over $22 billion in total reserves with a reserve-to-funded loan ratio of 2.7%."

Economic Outlook - Citigroup

The economic outlook is cautiously optimistic, with the U.S. remaining a key driver of global growth due to both consumer spending and a strong corporate sector. While China's growth has been slower than expected, there's potential for further stimulus, and emerging markets present bright spots. Management expects 2025 to resemble 2024, with ongoing impacts from central bank policies and global events.

  • "From the global macro perspective, economies have done a good job tolerating hikes from central banks and inflation has clearly been receiving. While policies will certainly impact economic activity, whether in the form of tariffs or taxes, 2025 doesn't look that different from '24."
  • "The U.S. remains at the heart of the macro picture. Growth is not only being driven by the higher-end consumer, but also by a strong innovative corporate sector."

Growth And Profitability - Discover Financial Services

Discover Financial Services demonstrated strong growth and profitability in Q4 2024 and throughout the year, driven by increased net interest margin, the sale of the student loan portfolio, and a reduction in provision expense. The company reported full year net income of $4.5 billion and earnings per share of $17.72, showcasing the benefits of strategic initiatives and a favorable economic environment.

  • "We reported net income of $4.5 billion for the full year 2024, and earnings per share of $17.72, reflecting several factors."
  • "In the fourth quarter, we reported net income of $1.3 billion versus $366 million in the same period last year. These results were driven by 3 main factors."

Lending Activities - Discover Financial Services

Lending activities saw a mixed performance, with card receivables increasing slightly but card sales decreasing due to previous credit tightening. However, personal loans showed growth, and overall, the company is taking a conservative approach to underwriting while preparing to increase new account acquisition in the coming year.

  • "Card receivables increased 1% year-over-year due to a slightly lower payment rate, partially offset by a decrease in sales volume."
  • "Personal loans were up 5% from the prior year. Demand remains strong and we continue to take a conservative approach to underwriting."

Credit Performance - Discover Financial Services

Credit performance showed signs of improvement, with net charge-offs declining from the prior quarter and delinquency rates stabilizing, particularly in the card segment. The company's view on the consumer remains stable, supported by wage growth and a resilient labor market, and they continue to monitor the performance of different loan vintages.

  • "In card, net charge-offs declined 25 basis points from the prior quarter, and the 30-plus day delinquency rate was flat. This marks the third consecutive quarter that card net charge-off rate has declined."
  • "We are seeing improvements across the portfolio. Personal loan net charge-offs and delinquencies continue to be within historical norms. Increases reflect the seasoning of recent growth."

Economic Outlook - Discover Financial Services

Management maintains a relatively stable outlook on the economy, anticipating continued consumer strength supported by wage growth and a resilient labor market. Their GDP forecast remains in the 1% to 3% range, and the company expects loan growth to align more closely with pre-pandemic norms in the coming year.

  • "Our view on the consumer has not changed. We continue to observe a stable consumer supported by wage growth and a resilient labor market, providing a foundation for sales and credit headed into 2025."
  • "In terms of the macroeconomic outlook, our expectations for unemployment and GDP are relatively unchanged from last quarter. We now assume peak unemployment of 4.7%, up 10 basis points. Our GDP forecast remains in the 1% to 3% range."

Growth And Profitability - Bread Financial

Bread Financial experienced mixed results in Q4 2024. While they added new brand partners and credit sales grew slightly year-over-year, revenue and adjusted diluted EPS decreased due to lower finance charges, late fees, and net interest income. However, they achieved positive operating leverage by lowering expenses and met their full-year targets, demonstrating resilience in a challenging macroeconomic environment.

  • "We achieved all of our 2024 full year targets in spite of a more challenging than anticipated macroeconomic environment."
  • "We generated adjusted income from continuing operations of $21 million and adjusted diluted EPS from continuing operations of $0.41."

Lending Activities - Bread Financial

Bread Financial's lending activities were focused on strategic partnerships, including securing renewals and adding new partners in diverse industry verticals. The company also experienced loan growth in co-brand and proprietary products, driven by increased spending in non-discretionary categories during the holiday season, while actively monitoring economic and political uncertainties.

  • "With the addition of these new brand partners, along with continued strong renewal rates, including 7 renewals in 2024, we now have more than 85% of our loans secured through 2026 and 9 out of our top 10 programs secured through at least 2028."
  • "Spending continues to be more heavily weighted towards nondiscretionary purchases, leading to strong loan growth in our co-brand and proprietary products during the holidays."

Credit Performance - Bread Financial

Bread Financial proactively tightened credit standards during the year, which helped to maintain a stable credit risk distribution despite macroeconomic pressures. Gross credit losses were elevated during the year and contributed to lower average loans, although the company benefited from a lower provision for credit losses during the fourth quarter.

  • "Our strategic, proactive credit tightening actions during the year enabled us to maintain a stable credit risk distribution."
  • "average loans of $18.2 billion decreased 1%, reflecting lower full year credit sales and elevated gross credit losses in the year."

Economic Outlook - Bread Financial

Bread Financial acknowledges ongoing economic and political uncertainties, including the impact of legislative and monetary policies. Despite these uncertainties, the company expresses cautious optimism for continued credit sales improvement in 2025, driven by new and existing partner growth, but they continue to monitor the situation closely.

  • "While we continue to closely monitor ongoing economic and political uncertainties, including impacts from key legislative and monetary policies, we are cautiously optimistic that credit sales improvement will continue in 2025 driven by new and existing partner growth."
  • "The macroeconomic and regulatory environments evolved throughout 2024. In turn, we effectively adapted to prolonged inflationary pressures affecting our customers and uncertainty regarding regulatory outcomes."

Growth And Profitability - Synchrony Financial

Synchrony achieved a solid close to 2024 with growth in new accounts, purchase volume, and ending loan receivables. This performance drove strong full-year net earnings, return on average assets, and return on tangible common equity, although these results included the positive and adverse impacts of nonrecurring events.

  • "We added 5 million new accounts, generated $48 billion of purchase volume and grew ending loan receivables by 2%."
  • "As a result, Synchrony generated full year 2024 net earnings of $3.5 billion or $8.55 per diluted share, a return on average assets of 2.9% and a return on tangible common equity of 27.5%."

Lending Activities - Synchrony Financial

Synchrony is focused on diversifying its lending portfolio through new partnerships and expanding existing ones. They are also focused on broadening the utility of their products and markets they serve through the acquisition of Ally Lending and the expansion of buy now, pay later options.

  • "During 2024, we added more than 45 new partners, including iconic brands like Virgin, Gibson and BRP as well as technology-oriented relationships like Adit Practice Management Software and ServiceTitan."
  • "In 2024, we completed the acquisition of the Ally Lending business and are in the process of transitioning merchants to Synchrony Pay Later."

Credit Performance - Synchrony Financial

Synchrony observed improvement in its year-over-year delinquency trends. They continue to use advanced data analytics and deep lending expertise to remain responsive in a rapidly changing environment and optimize risk-adjusted returns.

  • "In addition, we continue to see improvement in our portfolios year-over-year delinquency trends."
  • "Synchrony leveraged our scale, our data analytics and deep lending expertise and our advanced digital capabilities to remain nimble and responsive in a rapidly changing environment."

Economic Outlook - Synchrony Financial

The management acknowledged that customers are becoming more discerning in their spending choices due to persistent inflation. The company is monitoring this environment closely and believes they are positioned for sustainable growth.

  • "And so even as customers became more discerning in their spending choices and the impacts of persistent inflation and our credit actions took hold as the year progressed..."
  • "...Synchrony executed at a high level across all our key strategic priorities to optimize our business and position us for sustainable growth at strong risk-adjusted returns for the long-term."

Growth And Profitability - JPMorgan

JPMorgan Chase demonstrated strong growth and profitability in 2024, achieving record revenue and net income, driven by robust performance across its various business segments. The firm's ROTCE remained strong, indicating efficient capital allocation and value creation for shareholders.

  • "2024 was another year of record revenue and net income, and we're proud of what we accomplished."
  • "Excluding those items, the firm reported net income of $54 billion, EPS of $18.22, revenue of $173 billion, and we delivered an ROTCE of 20%."

Lending Activities - JPMorgan

Lending activities showed mixed trends, with some areas experiencing growth and others contraction. While card outstandings increased, driven by strong account acquisition and revolver growth, wholesale lending saw a seasonal decline.

  • "Card outstandings were up 11% due to strong account acquisition and revolver growth."
  • "The $24 billion decrease in RWA reflects a seasonal decline in Markets activity and lower wholesale lending, which was predominantly offset by a seasonal increase in card."

Credit Performance - JPMorgan

Credit performance showed some deterioration, primarily in the card portfolio, with net charge-offs increasing year-on-year. The company increased its net reserve build, predominantly driven by higher card revolving balances, reflecting a cautious approach to potential future losses.

  • "In terms of credit performance this quarter, credit costs were $2.6 billion, reflecting net charge-offs of $2.1 billion, up $428 million year-on-year driven by card."
  • "The net reserve build was $557 million, predominantly driven by higher card revolving balances."

Economic Outlook - JPMorgan

The management expressed optimism about the strength of the franchise but acknowledged uncertainties and risks in the economic environment. They anticipated NII normalization and are prepared for a wide range of scenarios, reflecting a balanced view of potential future economic conditions.

  • "As we look ahead to 2025, we still expect NII normalization, although to a lesser extent than we previously thought."
  • "In that context, we remain upbeat about the strength of the franchise, but we are focused on being prepared for a wide range of scenarios."

Growth And Profitability - American Express

American Express delivered a strong 2024, achieving record revenues and net income, driven by increased Card Member spending and new card acquisitions. They are projecting continued growth in 2025, driven by their focus on premium customers and international expansion, with revenue growth expected between 8% to 10%.

  • "We delivered record revenues of $66 billion for the year, up 10% on an FX-adjusted basis, achieving our long-term aspiration."
  • "We expect 2025 revenue growth of 8% to 10% and EPS of $15 to $15.50 or a 12% to 16% increase over 2024 adjusted for the Accertify gain."

Lending Activities - American Express

American Express experienced healthy loan growth in 2024, and expects loans and receivables to grow slightly faster than spend in 2025. Their growth rates moderated in 2024 as they lapped the period when customers were building back revolving balances coming out of the pandemic.

  • "Q4 Total loans and Card Member receivables grew at 9% on an FX-adjusted basis versus last year."
  • "With that process largely behind us, for 2025, we expect loans and receivables growth to continue to grow a bit faster than spend..."

Credit Performance - American Express

The transcript mentions that American Express maintained best-in-class credit performance in 2024. However, specific details about delinquency rates, default rates, loan loss reserves or charge-offs are not available in the provided earnings call transcript excerpt.

  • "We achieved these results while maintaining our best-in-class credit performance, investing at high levels for growth as well as driving significant operating leverage."
  • "[No additional quotes available from transcript]"

Economic Outlook - American Express

American Express observed a stable spending environment for most of 2024 with an acceleration in spending as they exited the year, which has continued into the first weeks of January 2025. The company assumes a similar spending environment in 2025 to what they saw in 2024 on a full year basis but it too soon to tell if the Q4 momentum will sustain.

  • "We saw a stable spending environment for most of 2024 with an acceleration in spending as we exited the year."
  • "So as we think about 2025, we are assuming at this point, a similar spend environment to what we saw in 2024 on a full year basis."

Growth And Profitability - Capital One

Capital One demonstrated mixed growth and profitability trends in Q4 2024. While revenue increased, pre-provision earnings decreased due to higher noninterest expenses. The company reported adjusted EPS of $3.09 for the quarter and $13.96 for the full year.

  • "Pre-provision earnings of $4.1 billion in the fourth quarter were down 13% from the third quarter driven by higher noninterest expense."
  • "Revenue in the linked quarter increased 2% driven by higher noninterest income."

Lending Activities - Capital One

Capital One experienced growth in domestic card loans and auto originations, demonstrating a strategic approach to lending. The company tightened credit in 2023, which enabled it to capitalize on favorable marketplace conditions and drive originations growth in 2024.

  • "Year-over-year purchase volume growth for the quarter was 7%. Ending loan balances increased $8 billion or about 5% year-over-year."
  • "Auto originations were up 53% from the prior year quarter...These choices, really, basically, they drove strong and stable credit performance that positioned us to lean into current marketplace opportunities and return to originations growth in 2024."

Credit Performance - Capital One

Capital One's credit performance was generally stable with some areas of improvement and others showing a slight increase in risk. While the overall allowance for credit losses decreased due to releases in Commercial Banking and Consumer Banking, charge-off rates increased in both the Domestic Card and Auto businesses, albeit partially offset by the Walmart agreement impact.

  • "We released $245 million in allowance this quarter, and our allowance balance now stands at $16.3 billion."
  • "The charge-off rate for the quarter was 6.06%. The impact of the end of the Walmart loss-sharing agreement increased the fourth quarter charge-off rate by roughly 40 basis points. Excluding this impact, the charge-off rate for the quarter would have been 5.66%, up 31 basis points year-over-year."

Economic Outlook - Capital One

The transcript does not provide a clear summary of managements view on economic conditions and forecasts. However, there are insights into the consumer environment within the lending and credit performance analysis.

  • "[None]"

Growth And Profitability - Wells Fargo

Wells Fargo demonstrated solid performance in Q4 2024, with improving earnings driven by strong fee-based revenue growth and disciplined expense management. The bank is seeing benefits from strategic investments and efficiency initiatives, resulting in increased net income and diluted earnings per share compared to the previous year.

  • "Our solid performance this quarter caps a year of significant progress for Wells Fargo across multiple areas. Our earnings profile continues to improve."
  • "In 2024, our strong fee-based revenue growth, up 15% from a year ago, largely offset the expected decline in net interest income, reflecting these efforts."

Lending Activities - Wells Fargo

Average loans declined throughout the year, primarily due to weak loan demand and credit tightening, despite growth in credit card balances. The bank is strategically repositioning its home lending business and has entered into a co-branded agreement in the auto finance sector, indicating a focus on specific growth areas.

  • "Average loans declined throughout the year as credit card growth in credit card balances was offset by declines in most other asset classes, reflecting weak loan demand as well as credit tightening actions."
  • "In our auto business, we announced a multiyear co-branded agreement where we will be the preferred purchase finance provider for Volkswagen and Audi brands in the United States starting in the first half of this year."

Credit Performance - Wells Fargo

Credit performance remained relatively stable and consistent with expectations throughout the year, indicating strong credit discipline. While specific delinquency or charge-off rates aren't detailed in this excerpt, the overall tone suggests healthy credit quality.

  • "We maintained our strong credit discipline and credit performance was relatively stable throughout the year and consistent with our expectations."
  • "We've done this while maintaining our credit standards [referring to credit card growth]."

Economic Outlook - Wells Fargo

Management views the U.S. economy as strong, citing low inflation and unemployment as positive indicators for 2025. They are optimistic about the incoming administration's support for U.S. businesses and a potentially more business-friendly regulatory environment.

  • "More broadly, the U.S. economy has performed very well and remains strong and lower inflation and unemployment position the economy well into 2025."
  • "Additionally, the incoming administration has signaled a more business- friendly approach to policies and regulation, which should benefit the economy and our clients."

Growth And Profitability - Bank of America

Bank of America demonstrated solid growth and profitability in Q4 2024 and for the full year. Revenue increased across all categories, and net interest income (NII) exceeded expectations. Strong organic growth, particularly in deposits and client activity, contributed to healthy returns and positioned the bank well for continued growth in 2025.

  • "This morning, we reported $6.7 billion in net income. That is $0.82 in EPS for the fourth quarter. That was a solid finish to another good year at Bank of America."
  • "For the full year of 2024, we generated $102 billion of revenue and reported net income of $27 billion -- $27.1 billion or EPS of $3.21."

Lending Activities - Bank of America

Lending activities showed positive trends with growth in both consumer and commercial loans. Consumer loans grew in every category, and commercial loan demand strengthened significantly in the latter part of the year. The bank attributed this growth to a strong deposit franchise and disciplined pricing strategies.

  • "On the loan side, consumer loans grew in every category linked quarter. Commercial loan demand continued to build off the strengths we saw in third quarter of 2024 and commercial loans grew 5% year- over-year for the fourth quarter"
  • "We drove organic growth in all the businesses, and that we have highlighted on Slide 3. We saw continued growth in net new checking new households, new companies in Commercial Banking, growth in our institutional markets business. This organic activity enabled us to grow loans and deposits at a pace we believe is to be ahead of our industry average and our peers."

Credit Performance - Bank of America

Credit performance remained strong and asset quality stabilized, with net charge-offs declining modestly from the previous quarter. The bank observed that consumer credit was stabilizing to normal levels and commercial office losses were trending downward, both as previously anticipated. Provision expense remained consistent with the prior two quarters.

  • "Asset quality stabilized and remained strong with net charge-offs declining modestly from third quarter. Earlier in the year, we highlighted that our expectation on consumer credit is that they would stabilize to normal level. And on commercial office losses, they would trend down during the year."
  • "Provision expense for the quarter was $1.5 billion and was consistent with the previous 2 quarters."

Economic Outlook - Bank of America

Management indicated a positive, though moderate, economic outlook characterized by 2% to 3% GDP growth and healthy employment levels. Consumer spending remained resilient, and business clients were reported as profitable and liquid. The bank highlighted the strength of the American consumer based on their internal data.

  • "It kind of appears to be now settled into a 2% to 3% GDP type growth environment. It has healthy employment levels in the resilient consumer."
  • "So far in the first 2 weeks in January, their spending money at 4% to 5% clip over last year, similar to what they did in the fourth quarter. And on our business side, the clients are profitable, they're liquid and seeing good productivity."
